COMPETITION TIME! 💙🎁
In continuation and celebration of our beautiful ocean, we have partnered with @aquatech_imagingsolutions to host an ocean photo competition for a chance to win a $500 gift card from AquaTech!
To enter simply post one of your own original photographs that best represents what the ocean means to you. In the caption mention @Aquatech_imagingsolutions and @ocean plus use the hashtag #atoceancomp to have your photo enter the draw. The competition is open from ‪June 8-21‬, images can be captured on any device and multiple entries are accepted as long as posted from the 8th of June 2020. Our favourite images will have the chance to be featured on both AquaTech's and Ocean's Instagram pages with the final winner announced here ‪on June 24th.‬ Our winner will be chosen by a judging panel made up of ocean photographers @davesandford, @caitmiersphotography & @thurstonphoto.

For the full terms and conditions visit the link in our bio. #worldoceansday2020 #atoceancomp #aquatech
.
.
.
.This promotion is in no way sponsored, endorsed or administered by, or associated with Instagram.

We’ve joined with @sealegacy & @global_wildlife_conservation to share this unique and important perspective on the current state of our world.

#ExtinctionEndsHere

What comes after the Pandemic? This video message from the virus to humankind is a chilling reminder that our future is intimately connected with all other life on Earth. We know where the pandemic came from, and we know how to stop the next one. It's time to make our voices heard. Enough is enough. Now that our own vulnerability has been laid bare, it's time to demand #ExtinctionEndsHere -- for all life on Earth.

TAKE ACTION: ExtinctionEndsHere.org

Video: @SeaLegacy & @global_wildlife_conservation.

@shawnheinrichs @paulnicklen @mitty 💙

Felt urged to share this video from @racingextinction on the reality of our current plastic consumption.. 

It's PlasticFreeJuly! To truly tackle plastic pollution, we ultimately need to end the production of new single-use plastic and hold manufacturers responsible for their plastic waste, but in the meantime we can all play a role in combatting plastic pollution every day! Every single piece of plastic has the potential to harm or kill marine wildlife and each of us can make sure far less finds its way to the sea. #RefuseSingleUse plastic and try out our #FishFreeFriday campaign to make sure you're not contributing to the massive amounts of plastic pollution that come from the commercial fishing industry.
Video by @nataliekparra.
#OPSociety #RacingExtinction #PlasticFree

Trying to make sense of this breaking news.. the ocean on fire?? Yes.

Mexico’s state-owned oil company said a fire caused by a rupture in an undersea gas pipeline in the Gulf of Mexico is over, but videos showing efforts to put out what appears to be an underwater caldron of fire live on.

The "fire in the sea" was put out at 10:45 a.m. following a gas leak about 500 feet from a drilling platform, Pemex tweeted. No injuries were reported and the company said it took about 5 hours to bring the incident under control.

The company said it used boats to pump water over the underwater blaze, although nitrogen was also used to control the fire, Reuters reports, citing a Pemex incident report.

"Never in your life forget the time humans caught the ocean on fire and then tried to put it out by spraying water on it," tweeted podcaster Dave Anthony.

node.text:
An Eden’s whale trap feeding in the Gulf of Thailand. This extraordinary behavior (where the whale treads water!) is thought to have developed because pollution has made the Gulf of Thailand a hypoxic environment. Sewage outflows from the land have caused all the oxygen in the water to be used up, except at the surface. This means the whale’s fish prey can only live in this surface layer. By treading water and keeping the corners of their mouth below the surface, a flow is created pulling the fish into the whale's mouth. In the panic, some of the fish also seem to jump out of the water and into the whale’s mouth!⁣⁣
Video and Caption by @bertiegregory 💙

node.text:
Devastating news from @dolphindronedom 😰
•
The most tragic thing I’ve ever filmed: a pod of dolphins swimming through a giant oil spill. The spill is spanning an area covering more than 50 miles, and it is lurking just off the coast of San Diego. On today’s extended trip we made our way to our reliable Blue Whale hotspot near San Clemente Island and we were shocked when the whales seemingly vanished. Just 24 hours earlier this zone was full of the feeding giants. It was then that we began making our way south, and soon made this shocking discovery. Tragic doesn’t begin to cover it. For more than 50 miles the ocean was covered in a thick sheen of oil, a devastating tragedy for the environment. We know very little at this time, and we are trying to make these images go viral in hopes of getting some answers as to how this happened. More shocking yet, 70+ miles away back in coastal San Diego, the local whale watching boats reported an area thick with oil encroaching on the local waters as well. I truly hope this isn’t as bad as it appears, but if this oil is already in an area that spans at a minimum of 70 miles, we could have a catastrophe of unimaginable scale on our hands. Please share this video, we need answers. 
We’ve reached out to NOAA, the Coast Guard, and the EPA. We hope to have an update soon.
